Note:  We agree that the histologic appearance of the dermal infiltrate is highly suggestive of cutaneous involvement by classical Hodgkin lymphoma (CHL).  However, there are a number of features that prevent us from making a definitive diagnosis.  Both the site and the clinical history are extremely unusual for CHL, but the major impediment to establishing a definitive diagnosis is that the immunophenotype is also not completely characteristic.  All of the large cells show strong CD20 and PAX5-positivity, as well as some CD45 positivity.  CD30 staining is positive but somewhat weak for CHL, and CD15 is almost completely negative.

This is an extremely challenging case.  Since there are multiple infectious/inflammatory processes that can mimic many features of CHL, in the absence of a classic immunophenotype and in conjunction with the unusual site and clinical presentation, we are unable to make a definitive diagnosis of CHL.  There are numerous small background T-cells, as well as numerous variably-sized B-cells, but, in our opinion, the atypical lymphoid infiltrate does not meet the criteria for peripheral T-cell lymphoma or B-cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma either.  Antigen receptor PCR analyses for B-cell and T-cell clonality were performed in consideration of non-Hodgkin lymphoma and both were negative.  The case was reviewed at the **NAME[DDD FFF] Conference on **DATE[Mar 5 2012] by Drs. **NAME[VVV, UUU, TTT] and **NAME[SSS]: they concur with this interpretation.

Microscopic Description:  Hematoxylin and eosin stained sections of the skin punch tissue sampling show skin with a superficial to deep dense lymphocyte infiltration restricted to the dermis and not involving the overlying epidermis.  Scattered large atypical cells with prominent nucleoli and cytoplasmic clearing/retraction resembling classical Hodgkin lymphoma lacunar cells are present.  The background infiltrate is composed of numerous small lymphocytes, histiocytes, and occasional plasma cells.

Immunohistochemical Stains:  The following immunostains were received for review from the referring institution:  CD3, CD5, CD10, CD15, CD20, CD21, CD30, CD45, BCL2, BCL6, PAX 5 and EMA.  Limited additional immunostaining were performed at OHSU, using the CD3, CD15, CD20, CD30 and PAX 5 antibodies, which showed similar staining to the outside immunostains.  The large atypical cells show the following immunophenotype:
  CD3  negative
  CD5  negative
  CD10  negative
  CD15  rare positive cells
  CD20  strongly and homogenously positive
  CD30  variably positive
  CD45  variably positive
  BCL2  negative
  BCL6  occasional positive cell
  PAX 5  strongly positive

The background small lymphocytes are mainly CD3 and CD5-positive T-cells, but there are also numerous, variably-sized B-cells in the infiltrate, highlighted by staining with the CD20 and PAX 5 antibodies.

In Situ Hybridization:  Molecular probes were used in an localized tumor hybridization analysis for **NAME[RRR QQQ] virus encoded mRNA.  Appropriate controls, including RNA controls, were performed and test validity confirmed.  The large atypical cells are negative for Epstein-Barr virus on the localized tumor hybridization analysis.

Interpreted by:  **NAME[VVV M. UUU] MD
Comment:

1.  The guideline recommendations by ASCO/CAP in 2007 is as follows:  A
score of 3+ (positive HER2 test) is defined by uniform intense membrane
staining in >30% of tumor cells.  A score of 2+ (equivocal HER2 test) is
defined by complete membrane staining that is either nonuniform or weak
in intensity but with obvious circumferential distribution in at least
10% of tumor cells, or less commonly, intense complete membrane staining
but in only 30% or fewer tumor cells.  A score of 0 or 1+ (negative HER2
test) is defined by no or weak and incomplete membrane staining in any
proportion of tumor cells.
2.  The correlation between HER2 protein overexpression by
immunohistochemistry and HER2/neu gene amplification by fluorescence in
situ hybridization (FISH) is not 100%.  Rare cases interpreted as
negative (0 and 1+) for HER2 protein overexpression may demonstrate low
level HER2/neu gene amplification by FISH.  Approximately 10-20% of
cases interpreted as 2+ may show gene amplification by FISH, while the
vast majority of cases, if not all, interpreted as 3+ show gene
amplification by FISH.  Therefore, additional testing for HER2/neu gene
amplification by fluorescence localized tumor hybridization (FISH) may be
considered on individual cases, if clinically warranted.  Reflexive
testing for HER2/neu gene amplification by FISH will be performed on all
cases interpreted as 2+ (equivocal for protein overexpression) by
immunohistochemistry.   Performed at CellNetix Pathology  **PLACE, WA.  **ZIP-CODE.

The scant red-cell series is normoblastic.  The myeloid to erythroid ratio is approximately 3:1.  The scant myeloid cell lines show normal maturation.  There are adequate numbers of megakaryocytes.  No small area of inflammationta, extrinsic cells, vascular lesions or parasites are seen.

ASPIRATION SMEARS:  The smears confirm the findings noted above.  Lymphoblasts comprise approximately 80% of the nucleated cell population.  The blasts are predominantly small to occasional medium sized cells with scant cytoplasm, irregular shaped nuclear contour and rare inconspicuous nucleoli.  The scant numbers of myeloid and erythroid precursors show no evidence of maturation arrest.  There is no evidence of dyserythropoiesis or dysmyelopoiesis.

(dim) positive B-cells co-expressing CD5, CD23 and indeterminate (possibly
dim kappa) light chain. CD38 is expressed on <30% of clonal B-cells. This
immunophenotype and limited morphologic findings are characteristic for
chronic lymphocytic blood cancer (CLL).  If the patient does not have a
previously established diagnosis of CLL/SLL, the current requirement for
this diagnosis includes an absolute monoclonal B-cell count >5 x 10(9)/L,
or the presence of extramedullary tissue involvement, cytopenias or disease
related symptoms (WHO classification 2008).  The alternative diagnosis is
monoclonal B-cell lymphocytosis (MBL) with a CLL-like phenotype, which has
been shown to progress to CLL requiring therapy at a rate of \R\1% per year
(Rawstron et al NEJM 2008; **ID-NUM). If identifying disease criteria for CLL are
met, then the absence of CD38 expression is associated with better outcome.
(Ref. Matrai Z. Hematology 2005;10:39-46; Boonstra JG et al,
2006;**ID-NUM). Clinical and morphologic correlation is required for
complete interpretation of these findings, with periodic blood monitoring
recommended if clinically warranted.

A-B.  Bone marrow, right posterior iliac crest, aspirate and tissue sampling:
1.  Normocellular bone marrow (10-20% cellularity), suspicious for involvement by a mature B cell lymphoma (10% of total cells) (see Comment)
    a.  Rare stainable iron and no increase in ring sideroblasts
2.  Flow cytometric immunophenotyping demonstrates:
    a.   CD5-negative/CD10-negative B-cell subpopulation comprising 40% of lymphocytes/7-8% of the 
      total cells, with slightly decreased intensity CD19, bright CD20, and non-specific staining for 
      surface and cytoplasmic light chains.  This population shows light scatter features of small 
      cells.  
      Phenotype:   CD45-bright/CD19+(moderate)/CD20+(bright)/CD22-  /CD23- /CD5-  /CD10-  /
      CD38-.  Non-specific staining on analysis for surface and cytoplasmic light chains.
    b.  The remainder of the B-cells are surface light chain polytypic, have normal intensity CD19 and 
      bright CD20, and show light scatter features of small cells.  This population comprises 4% of 
      lymphocytes/less than 1% of the total cells.\E\
    c.  Phenotypically unremarkable peripheral T-cells and NK-cells.
3.  Cytogenetics:    
  a.  Major cell line:  45,X,-Y[3]
  b.  Minor cell line:  46,XY,del(11)(q14q23)[2]/46,XY[15]

Peripheral blood:
1.  Mild normochromic, normocytic anemia
DiagnosisComment:
Per EPIC, the patient has a prior diagnosis of a CD20-positive, follicular lymphoma, grade 3A out of 3 from a **DATE[Apr 15 12] excisional tissue sampling of left axillary lymphadenopathy. 

For the current bone marrow tissue sampling, the histologic and immunohistochemical findings show scattered, small B cells (10% of total cells).  A rare, loose, paratrabecular lymphoid aggregate is seen (see second photo).  The flow cytometry study identifies an atypical population of small B cells (although light chain restriction is not established).  Lastly, the cytogenetics data demonstrates a deletion in chromosome 11 in a subset of the cells (although this finding is not pathognomonic for any disease).  Collectively, these findings raise the suspicion, but are not definitive for, bone marrow involvement by a CD20-positive mature B cell lymphoma.

With the available data, a definitive diagnosis of a follicular lymphoma is not currently rendered because of 1)  the low level marrow involvement by the B cells (approximately only 10% of the total cells), 2) lack of a definitive population of light chain-restricted B cells by flow cytometry, 3) lack of a typical histologic pattern with corroborating immunohistochemical staining (i.e., BCL-2, BCL-6), and 4) lack of a typical t(14;18) genetic abnormality by cytogenetics.
Additional fluorescence localized tumor hybridization studies and molecular immunoglobulin heavy chain gene rearrangement studies are pending, and these results will be incorporated as Addenda for a final diagnosis.


Also, stainable marrow iron is rare.  If indicated, consider correlation with serologic studies.

Please also see the concurrent flow cytometry immunophenotyping report (PPPL at HMC **NAME[ZZZ] Flow Cytometry Laboratory, ***PATH-NUMBER[1]) and concurrent cytogenetics report (Ohana Genetics, **ID-NUM). |

AddendumDiagnosis:
A.   Bone marrow, aspiration:  
    1.    Bone marrow with an atypical B cell population (see Addendum Comment)
    2.  B cell clonality detection by PCR:  Insufficient DNA isolated (see Addendum Comment)
    3.    BCL6 rearrangement by FISH:  Not detected
    4.    IGH/BCL2 translocation by FISH:  Not detected.
AddendumComment:
This Addendum is created to incorporate an additional molecular B cell clonality and fluorescence localized tumor hybridization (FISH) studies.

A B cell clonality detection study (immunoglobulin gene rearrangement) by PCR was conducted to help identify a clonal B cell population.  However, insufficient DNA was isolated; and this study provides no additional data.

FISH studies examining for a BCL6 rearrangement and an IGH/BCL2 translocation were not detected.  

In summary, 1) the atypical morphologic findings of the bone marrow tissue sampling (i.e., rare paratrabecular lymphoid aggregate with numerous B cells), 2) atypical findings by flow cytometry (i.e. CD5-negative/CD10-negative B cells comprising 40% of lymphocytes/7-8% of total cells and with non-specific light chain staining), and 3) deletion in chromosome 11 in a subset of the cells are all findings which raise the suspicion for involvement by a low-grade mature B cell lymphoma.  However, these findings are not definitive for a diagnosis of malignant tumor.  The additional molecular B cell clonality study and FISH studies do not provide any further support for a clonal B cell population.  

It is possible that the lack of definitive data is related to sampling or the sensitivity of the molecular and FISH tests.

As mentioned earlier in the original Comments, a definitive diagnosis of a follicular lymphoma is not currently rendered because of 1) the low level marrow involvement by the B cells (approximately only 10% of the total cells), 2) lack of a definitive population of light chain-restricted B cells by flow cytometry, 3) lack of a identifying disease histologic pattern with corroborating immunohistochemical staining (i.e., BCL-2, BCL-6), 4) lack of a typical t(14;18) genetic abnormality by cytogenetics, and 5) lack of a detectable IGH/BCL2 or BCL6 rearrangement.

Please also see Clarient reports ***PATH-NUMBER[2] (B cell clonality detection) and ***PATH-NUMBER[3] (FISH studies).

The tumor is arranged as rounded and angulated nests of cells. Moderate to abundant amounts of granular pink cytoplasm are seen. The nuclei are rather uniform and an occasional inconspicuous nucleolus is seen. Mitotic activity is very low with only a rare mitotic figure identified. Necrosis is not seen. B. Step sections of the bronchial margin of surgical removal of tissue from the left upper lobe of lung reveal no evidence of malignant tumor. The bronchus is lined by ciliated pseudostratified columnar epithelium. The submucosal glands are unremarkable. Sections from the surgically clipped parenchymal surgical borders of surgical removal of tissue reveal no evidence of neoplasia. Many macrophages are seen in the alveolar spaces and many of these macrophages contain anthracotic pigment. Step sections of the left upper lobe of lung mass reveal histologic changes of typical carcinoid. Large groups of cells are seen demonstrating moderate to abundant amounts of granular amphophilic cytoplasm. The nuclei are generally round to oval and demonstrate a stippled chromatin pattern. Mitotic activity is low. Focal nuclear pleomorphism is seen. Necrosis is not identified. The tumor may be seen undermining bronchial mucosa. Immunohistochemical stains performed at Genzyme confirm neuroendocrine differentiation. A random section of lung reveals no evidence of neoplasia. Intra-alveolar bleeding is seen. Scattered foci of anthracotic pigment deposition are seen. Anthracotic laden macrophages may be seen within alveolar spaces. Sections of the vascular surgical borders of surgical removal of tissue reveal no evidence of neoplasia. Sections of the peribronchial lymph nodes reveal 2 out of 2 lymph nodes to be negative for metastatic malignant tumor. There is prominent sinus histiocytosis. Sections from the remaining segments of lung tissue, including the parenchymal surgical borders of surgical removal of tissue, reveal no evidence of neoplasia. Hemorrhage is seen within alveolar spaces. Anthracotic pigment laden macrophages are also seen within alveolar spaces. There is scattered anthracotic pigment deposition. Emphysematous changes are seen with coalescence of alveolar spaces noted. C. Step sections of the left peribronchial lymph node reveal a lymph node demonstrating a hyalinized and calcified small lump compatible with a remote small area of inflammation. Sinus histiocytosis is also seen within the lymph node. There is no evidence of metastatic malignant tumor. D. Sections of the level V lymph node reveal no histologic evidence of malignant tumor. COMMENTS:
The results of the immunohistochemistry panel for this poorly differentiated mixed malignant tumor of connective tissuetoid and epithelioid malignant tumor confirm the suspicion of a metastatic malignant epithelial tumor (uniformly positive with pancytokeratins OSCAR), and given the provided clinical history, are considered consistent with a spread of cancer from the patient's known lung malignant epithelial tumor. Spindle cell malignant epithelial tumors of the lung typically show no expression of lung organ-specific markers (such as TTF-1), as exemplified in this particular case. Otherwise, there is no evidence for a skin cancer (negative S100/HMB45), myogenic malignant tumor of connective tissue (negative desmin), vascular malignant tumor of connective tissue (negative CD34), or an astrocytic malignant tumor (negative GFAP).

This Addendum is created to incorporate additional immunohistochemical staining results for part C.

For Part C (cardia lesser curvature), additional immunohistochemical stains were conducted in an attempt to further characterize the neoplasm.  Unfortunately, the small amount of neoplastic cells in the original hematoxylin and eosin-stained sections does not appear in the deeper, immunohistochemically stained tissue sections (conducted for this Addendum), thereby precluding further characterization.  

The morphologic features and the prior immunohistochemical stains (i.e., CD56 and synaptophysin) suggest a poorly-differentiated neuroendocrine neoplasm, favoring small cell malignant epithelial tumor.  However, in the absence of a full immunohistochemical work-up, other malignancies (i.e., atypical forms of hematopoietic neoplasms, gastrointestinal stromal tumor) cannot be definitively excluded.

If indicated, consider submission of more tissue/sampling of tumor to aid the diagnosis.
